{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","parts":[{"id":"prt_d73e12f9d001jVnr84op1RLGln","messageID":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","sessionID":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7840d25468fa49b1962b7ea1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/Makefile"},"output":"<path>/workspace/Makefile</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: COMMIT_HASH := $(shell eval git rev-parse HEAD)\n2: \n3: download-datasets:\n4: \tpython -c \"from river import datasets, bandit; datasets.Elec2().download(); datasets.SMSSpam().download(); bandit.datasets.NewsArticles().download()\"\n5: \n6: format:\n7: \tpre-commit run --all-files\n8: \n9: execute-notebooks:\n10: \tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/introduction/*/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n11: \tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/recipes/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n12: \tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/examples/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n13: \tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/examples/*/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n14: \n15: render-notebooks:\n16: \tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/introduction/*/*.ipynb\n17: \tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/recipes/*.ipynb\n18: \tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/examples/*.ipynb\n19: \tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/examples/*/*.ipynb\n20: \n21: doc: render-notebooks\n22: \tpython docs/parse river --out docs --verbose\n23: \tzensical build\n24: \n25: livedoc: doc\n26: \tzensical serve\n27: \n28: rebase:\n29: \tgit fetch && git rebase origin/main\n30: \n31: fomo:\n32: \tgit fetch && git rebase origin/main\n\n(End of file - total 32 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"COMMIT_HASH := $(shell eval git rev-parse HEAD)\n\ndownload-datasets:\n\tpython -c \"from river import datasets, bandit; datasets.Elec2().download(); datasets.SMSSpam().download(); bandit.datasets.NewsArticles().download()\"\n\nformat:\n\tpre-commit run --all-files\n\nexecute-notebooks:\n\tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/introduction/*/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n\tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/recipes/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n\tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/examples/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n\tjupyter nbconvert --execute --to notebook --inplace docs/examples/*/*.ipynb --ExecutePreprocessor.timeout=-1\n\nrender-notebooks:\n\tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/introduction/*/*.ipynb\n\tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/recipes/*.ipynb\n\tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/examples/*.ipynb\n\tjupyter nbconvert --to markdown docs/examples/*/*.ipynb\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"Makefile","time":{"start":1775765631307,"end":1775765631314}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","parts":[{"id":"prt_d73e1314d001z684vI0rWiVKGC","messageID":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","sessionID":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_afd5df8adce24bbab90bdcd2","state":{"status":"running","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md"},"time":{"start":1775765631740}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","parts":[{"id":"prt_d73e1314d001z684vI0rWiVKGC","messageID":"msg_d73e1240f001prfus6cOcX7lN2","sessionID":"ses_28c1ef03cffeb1iaPGU6wpB1W9","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_afd5df8adce24bbab90bdcd2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Contribution guidelines\n2: \n3: ## What to work on?\n4: \n5: We have a [public roadmap](https://github.com/orgs/online-ml/projects/3) that lists what has been done, what we're currently doing, and what needs doing. There's also an icebox with high level ideas that need framing. You're welcome to pick anything that takes your fancy and that you deem important. Feel free to [open a discussion](https://github.com/online-ml/river/discussions/new) if you want to clarify a topic and/or want to be formally assigned a task in the board.\n6: \n7: Of course, you're welcome to propose and contribute new ideas. We encourage you to [open a discussion](https://github.com/online-ml/river/discussions/new) so that we can align on the work to be done. It's generally a good idea to have a quick discussion before opening a pull request that is potentially out-of-scope.\n8: \n9: ## Fork/clone/pull\n10: \n11: The typical workflow for contributing to River is:\n12: \n13: 1. Fork the `main` branch from the [GitHub repository](https://github.com/online-ml/river/).\n14: 2. Clone your fork locally.\n15: 3. Commit changes.\n16: 4. Push the changes to your fork.\n17: 5. Send a pull request from your fork back to the original `main` branch.\n18: \n19: ## Local setup\n20: \n21: Start by cloning the repository:\n22: \n23: ```sh\n24: git clone --single-branch https://github.com/online-ml/river\n25: ```\n26: \n27: > **Note:** The `--single-branch` flag is important. Without it, Git will also fetch the `gh-pages` branch which contains the generated documentation site, adding several hundred MiB to the clone.\n28: \n29: Next, you'll need a Python environment. A nice way to manage your Python versions is to use pyenv, which can installed [here](https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv-installer). Once you have pyenv, you can install the latest Python version River supports:\n30: \n31: ```sh\n32: pyenv install -v $(cat .python-version)\n33: ```\n34: \n35: You need a `Rust` compiler you can install it by following this [link](https://www.rust-lang.org/fr/tools/install). You'll also need [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/):\n36: \n37: ```sh\n38: curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh\n39: ```\n40: \n41: Now you're set to install River:\n42: \n43: ```sh\n44: uv sync\n45: ```\n46: \n47: Finally, install the [pre-commit](https://pre-commit.com/) push hooks. This will run some code quality checks every time you push to GitHub.\n48: \n49: ```sh\n50: uv run pre-commit install --hook-type pre-push\n51: ```\n52: \n53: You can optionally run `pre-commit` at any time as so:\n54: \n55: ```sh\n56: uv run pre-commit run --all-files\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ## Making changes\n60: \n61: You're now ready to make some changes. We strongly recommend that you to check out River's source code for inspiration before getting into the thick of it. How you make the changes is up to you of course. However we can give you some pointers as to how to test your changes. Here is an example workflow that works for most cases:\n62: \n63: - Create and open a Jupyter notebook at the root of the directory.\n64: - Add the following in the code cell:\n65: \n66: ```py\n67: %load_ext autoreload\n68: %autoreload 2\n69: ```\n70: \n71: - The previous code will automatically reimport River for you whenever you make changes.\n72: - For instance, if a change is made to `linear_model.LinearRegression`, then rerunning the following code doesn't require rebooting the notebook:\n73: \n74: ```py\n75: from river import linear_model\n76: \n77: model = linear_model.LinearRegression()\n78: ```\n79: \n80: ## Creating a new estimator\n81: \n82: 1. Pick a base class from the `base` module.\n83: 2. Check if any of the mixin classes from the `base` module apply to your implementation.\n84: 3. Make you've implemented the required methods, with the following exceptions:\n85:    1. Stateless transformers do not require a `learn_one` method.\n86:    2. In case of a classifier, the `predict_one` is implemented by default, but can be overridden.\n87: 4. Add type hints to the parameters of the `__init__` method.\n88: 5. If possible provide a default value for each parameter. If, for whatever reason, no good default exists, then implement the `_unit_test_params` method. This is a private method that is meant to be used for testing.\n89: 6. Write a comprehensive docstring with example usage. Try to have empathy for new users when you do this.\n90: 7. Check that the class you have implemented is imported in the `__init__.py` file of the module it belongs to.\n91: 8. When you're done, run the `utils.check_estimator` function on your class and check that no exceptions are raised.\n92: \n93: ## Documenting your change\n94: \n95: If you're adding a class or a function, then you'll need to add a docstring. We follow the [Numpy docstring convention](https://numpydoc.readthedocs.io/en/latest/format.html), so please do too.\n96: \n97: To build the documentation, you need to install some extra dependencies:\n98: \n99: ```sh\n100: uv sync --group docs\n101: ```\n102: \n103: From the root of the repository, you can then run the `make livedoc` command to take a look at the documentation in your browser. This will run a custom script which parses all the docstrings and generate MarkDown files that [MkDocs](https://www.mkdocs.org/) can render.\n104: \n105: ## Adding a release note\n106: \n107: All classes and function are automatically picked up and added to the documentation. The only thing you have to do is to add an entry to the relevant file in the [`docs/releases` directory](docs/releases).\n108: \n109: ## Build Cython and Rust extensions\n110: \n111: ```sh\n112: uv sync\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ## Testing\n116: \n117: **Unit tests**\n118: \n119: These tests absolutely have to pass.\n120: \n121: ```sh\n122: uv run pytest\n123: ```\n124: \n125: **Static typing**\n126: \n127: These tests absolutely have to pass.\n128: \n129: ```sh\n130: uv run mypy river\n131: ```\n132: \n133: **Web dependent tests**\n134: \n135: This involves tests that need an internet connection, such as those in the `datasets` module which requires downloading some files. In most cases you probably don't need to run these.\n136: \n137: ```sh\n138: uv run pytest -m web\n139: ```\n140: \n141: **Notebook tests**\n142: \n143: You don't have to worry too much about these, as we only check them before each release. If you break them because you changed some code, then it's probably because the notebooks have to be modified, not the other way around.\n144: \n145: ```sh\n146: uv run make execute-notebooks\n147: ```\n148: \n149: ## Making a new release\n150: \n151: 1. Checkout `main`\n152: 2. Run `uv run make execute-notebooks` just to be safe\n153: 3. Run the [benchmarks](benchmarks)\n154: 4. Bump the version in `river/__version__.py`\n155: 5. Bump the version in `pyproject.toml`\n156: 6. Tag and date the `docs/releases/unreleased.md` file\n157: 7. Commit and push\n158: 8. Wait for CI to [run the unit tests](https://github.com/online-ml/river/actions/workflows/ci.yml)\n159: 9. Push the tag:\n160: \n161: ```sh\n162: RIVER_VERSION=$(uv run python -c \"import river; print(river.__version__)\")\n163: echo $RIVER_VERSION\n164: ```\n165: \n166: ```sh\n167: git tag $RIVER_VERSION\n168: git push origin $RIVER_VERSION\n169: ```\n170: \n171: 9. Wait for CI to [ship to PyPI](https://github.com/online-ml/river/actions/workflows/pypi.yml) and [publish the new docs](https://github.com/online-ml/river/actions/workflows/release-docs.yml)\n172: 10. Create a [release](https://github.com/online-ml/river/releases):\n173: \n174: ```sh\n175: RELEASE_NOTES=$(cat <<-END\n176: - https://riverml.xyz/${RIVER_VERSION}/releases/${RIVER_VERSION}/\n177: - https://pypi.org/project/river/${RIVER_VERSION}/\n178: END\n179: )\n180: brew update && brew install gh\n181: gh release create $RIVER_VERSION --notes $RELEASE_NOTES\n182: ```\n183: \n184: 11. Pyodide needs to be told there is a new release. This can done by updating [`packages/river`](https://github.com/online-ml/pyodide/tree/main/packages/river) in [online-ml/pyodide](https://github.com/online-ml/pyodide)\n\n(End of file - total 184 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Contribution guidelines\n\n## What to work on?\n\nWe have a [public roadmap](https://github.com/orgs/online-ml/projects/3) that lists what has been done, what we're currently doing, and what needs doing. There's also an icebox with high level ideas that need framing. You're welcome to pick anything that takes your fancy and that you deem important. Feel free to [open a discussion](https://github.com/online-ml/river/discussions/new) if you want to clarify a topic and/or want to be formally assigned a task in the board.\n\nOf course, you're welcome to propose and contribute new ideas. We encourage you to [open a discussion](https://github.com/online-ml/river/discussions/new) so that we can align on the work to be done. It's generally a good idea to have a quick discussion before opening a pull request that is potentially out-of-scope.\n\n## Fork/clone/pull\n\nThe typical workflow for contributing to River is:\n\n1. Fork the `main` branch from the [GitHub repository](https://github.com/online-ml/river/).\n2. Clone your fork locally.\n3. Commit changes.\n4. Push the changes to your fork.\n5. Send a pull request from your fork back to the original `main` branch.\n\n## Local setup\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"CONTRIBUTING.md","time":{"start":1775765631740,"end":1775765631745}}}]}
